    <segment id="1" parent="54" relname="preparation">
     
     I find myself compelled to take a few minutes to join the fray of 
     this discussion.</segment>
    <segment id="2" parent="3" relname="concession">
     
     Indeed, FULLER has dichotomized STS unto extremes.</segment>
    <segment id="3" parent="53" relname="span">
     But I think Steve&apos;s &apos;pure type&apos; reflexion is useful.</segment>
    <segment id="4" parent="35" relname="span">
     Do we, as STSers, polemicize the debate</segment>
    <segment id="32" parent="4" relname="condition"> if
     we claim disciplinary immunity for our research?</segment>
    <segment id="5" parent="6" relname="antithesis">  On what basis can
     we make that claim for ourselves,</segment>
    <segment id="6" parent="34" relname="span"> yet deny it to the &apos;hard sciences&apos;?
     Are we not as subject to constructed views of the universe as are they?</segment>
    <segment id="7" parent="36" relname="span">
     How is what &apos;interests&apos; us different from what &apos;interests&apos; the
     &apos;physical&apos; sciences? </segment>
    <segment id="8" parent="7" relname="elaboration"> (cf. Malcolm Ashmore&apos;s _Reflexive Thesis_)</segment>
    <segment id="9" parent="37" relname="span">  How
     can we ask the &apos;hard sciences&apos; to be open to our own criticisms 
     and not be open to theirs? </segment>
    <segment id="10" parent="9" relname="elaboration">Ditto re: openess to &apos;external&apos; normative 
     factors.</segment>
    <segment id="11" parent="12" relname="nonvolitional-cause">

     Moreover, how can we ask any academic discipline to be open
     to &apos;external&apos; normative shaping without taking-up the cause of
     being open to broader &apos;democratic&apos; norms?</segment>
    <segment id="12" parent="38" relname="span">

     Thus, should we let the &apos;lay public&apos; decide about how much, what, and
     who, both in the &apos;natural&apos; and the &apos;social&apos; sciences, gets funding?</segment>
    <segment id="13" parent="39" relname="span">
     The NEA has already been engaging in such debates in relation to 
     funding for &apos;the Arts&apos; and has steadfastly maintained that laypersons
     cannot decide what is Art -- that the &apos;norms&apos; of &apos;middle America&apos;
     should not dictate definitions of Art, lest Art become unilateral and
     unidimensional. </segment>
    <segment id="14" parent="13" relname="elaboration"> Would the so-called &quot;Academic Left&quot; support that 
     position for NEA but not for &apos;hard science&apos;? </segment>
    <segment id="15" parent="39" relname="elaboration"> And what about for
     STS, itself?</segment>
    <segment id="16" parent="49" relname="span">

     This gets us to RON EGLASH&apos;s position (paraphrased &amp; interpreted):</segment>
    <segment id="17" parent="18" relname="volitional-cause">
     Put &apos;diverse&apos; peoples in science,</segment>
    <segment id="18" parent="41" relname="span"> and the norms of science will move
     away from &apos;middle America science&apos; norms. </segment>
    <segment id="19" parent="48" relname="preparation"> My quite genuine question
     is:</segment>
    <segment id="20" parent="42" relname="disjunction"> Do we have evidence that &apos;science community&apos; norms will change,</segment>
    <segment id="21" parent="42" relname="disjunction">
     or can we more likely predict that &apos;personal&apos; norms will change to
     reflect the existing norms of science? </segment>
    <segment id="22" parent="23" relname="concession"> I realize that this, to
     use Giddens&apos; words, is a duality of process,</segment>
    <segment id="23" parent="45" relname="span"> but would I be naive 
     to predict the former will outpace the latter?</segment>
    <segment id="24" parent="25" relname="antithesis">

     If we accept that any academic discipline -- be it art, &apos;natural&apos;
     or &apos;social&apos; science, should be open to &apos;external&apos; normative shaping,
     even from &apos;non-academicians&apos;,</segment>
    <segment id="25" parent="46" relname="span"> how can academicians construct
     legitimized &apos;expertise&apos;? </segment>
    <segment id="26" parent="43" relname="span">  Indeed, my personal opinion is that this
     is the critical question that will face _all_ of academia in the very
     near future.</segment>
    <segment id="27" parent="26" relname="background">  Thus, my own interest in &apos;non-modern&apos; models of the
     universe.</segment>
    <segment id="28" parent="29" relname="antithesis">  And, if we as &apos;social scientists&apos; cannot move beyond
     the simple (if sometime useful) dichotomy model of the modern era,</segment>
    <segment id="29" parent="47" relname="span">
     how can we criticize &apos;natural scientists&apos; who cling to such 
     models?</segment>
    <segment id="30" parent="56" relname="span">

     Indeed, the game&apos;s afoot!</segment>
    <segment id="31" parent="30" relname="concession">  But I wonder if, in the end, the playoff
     will be between &apos;natural&apos; and &apos;social&apos; scientists or between
     modernists and non-modernists (to adapt a phrase from Latour so
     as to be distinguishable from &apos;postmodernist&apos;)?</segment>
